latestIgtvVideos.title: Let Flames of Creativity Burn and Survive Pandemic!
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
It's beautiful if you can see how to reuse resources at an era where people prefer running behind earning money and buying new stuffs. It's a bliss for the nature if you consume less and use your creativity to revamp things. It doesn't show that you are poor, rather it shows you are responsible and sensible humans! This pandemic has taught us a lot of things and indeed the sense of creativity is one thing that keeps me going.... 
The power of creation is so empowering.  Bring it on❤️
Be it anything, keep CREATING. 

Gratitude for Papa and Shreya.🤗

latestPosts.caption:
“Bonne Femme” – The Essence of a Good Woman, Served on a Plate
📍@bonnefemmekolkata 
Nestled in the artsy alleys of Hindustan Park, Kolkata, Bonne Femme is more than just a café — it’s an experience. With its soft French aesthetics, vintage corners, and the gentle hum of conversation, this place feels like a warm hug.

I stopped by for a quiet afternoon and was instantly swept away by the aroma of freshly brewed Hazelnut Cappuccino. Aam pora Sharbat is a must try for summers. But the real star? Their Mushroom Vol-au-vent — flaky, buttery pastry filled with creamy mushrooms that melt in your mouth. I tried their chilli baby corn with kaffir lime 🍋‍🟩 and chhanar galauti kebaab, both giving very refreshing flavours making it stand different than usual !

Perfect for book lovers, coffee dates, or solo journaling sessions, Bonne Femme wraps you in calm and leaves your taste buds smiling. A hidden gem I’ll keep returning to.

⸻

latestPosts.caption:
I came across the Japanese phrase
“mono no aware” the other day. It translates to mean “an empathy toward things” or a “sensitivity to ephemera” an acute awareness of impermanence or transience of things, and both a transient gentle sadness (or wistfulness) at their passing. Growing up, I think I always felt a tinge of sadness in moments that felt special because ultimately, I think I knew how much I was going to feel about this moment in hindsight. That same sadness eventually made me wistful, fanciful even about a lot of things- no matter how small they might feel at the time. Like having the privilege to just sit and enjoy the view rather than having limited time to absorb about the characters around. Or the feeling of being driven by a parent, as you’re gently falling asleep in the backseat, en route home. Or travelling to a new country where you face a lot of difficulties but still you know you are going to remember this for years to come, so you need to feel special for being there despite of all the odds. This is what life is, where anything and everything could happen, and in some magical way, it does, that is what I have built my believe system in.
While it might seem hard to let the sadness and joy coexist in these fleeting moments, I take comfort in knowing that one informs the other. The sadness just underscores how much that moment really meant to me. And my joy stems from that understanding.

So no, my life isn’t a fairytale always but now you know:
“Why do you make everything so special?”

Shinzo wo Sasageyo !

Nestled in the heart of Bavaria, Germany, Nördlingen is a charming medieval town built inside a massive 15-million-year-old meteorite crater. Its preserved city walls and historic half-timbered houses inspired the setting of Attack on Titan.
You can reach Nördlingen by train from Munich (approx. 2.5 hours) or from Stuttgart via Aalen.

The most efficient way to reach is to take:

🚆 Train from Cologne to Wuppertal
	•	Departure Station: Köln Hauptbahnhof (Cologne Central Station) ￼
	•	Arrival Station: Wuppertal Hauptbahnhof (Wuppertal Hbf)
	•	Train Options:
	•	RB48 (Rhein-Wupper-Bahn): Approximately 40 minutes ￼
	•	RE7 (Regional-Express): Approximately 30 minutes ￼
	•	IC/ICE (Intercity/Intercity Express): Approximately 28–36 minutes ￼
	•	Ticket Prices: Start at around €11–€15 one-way. Booking in advance may offer better rates 
Deutschland-Ticket (€49 Monthly Pass): This pass covers regional trains, the Schwebebahn, and local transport in both Cologne and Wuppertal, making it a cost-effective option if you’re planning multiple trips . ￼
	•	Single Tickets: Single tickets for the train and Schwebebahn are also available.
